lish <i>Ducc(a)</i>, but was more often a pet form of <i>Marmaduke</i>, especially in Yorkshire (see   Duke  ). <i>Marmaduke</i> itself is from Irish <i>Maol Maedóc</i> ‘servant of Maedóc’, <i>Maedóc</i> being the name of prominent Irish saints of the 6th and 7th centuries."],"variants":[{"name":"Dockett","meanings":["English (Devon): variant of   Duckett  . Alternatively, the name may have arisen from Middle English <i>doke heved</i> ‘duck head’ but there is no evidence that this became a hereditary surname."]},{"name":"Doggett","meanings":["English: variant of   Duckett   with voicing of the medial consonant. Alternatively, the name may also be from a Middle English rhyming pet form of <i>Roger</i> (see   Dodge  ) + the diminutive suffix <i>-et</i>. But whether the medial <i>-g-</i> was pronounced as a stop /g/ (as in <i>dog</i>) or an affricate /dʒ/ (as in <i>Roger</i>) is impossible to tell."]},{"name":"Duke","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>duk(ke)</i>, <i>duck</i>, <i>doke</i>, <i>dook</i> ‘duck’ (Old English <i>dūce</i>), either from a perceived resemblance (perhaps a waddling gait) or from association with wild fowling. Compare   Duck  ,   Drake  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Duk</i> or <i>Duke</i>. In northern England this is usually a pet form of <i>Marmaduke</i>. It may alternatively be a survival of one or more Old English personal names, though it is uncertain whether they were still current in the period of surname formation. Old English <i>Ducc(a)</i> is attested in placenames like Duxford (Cambridgeshire) and Duckington (Cheshire), and was perhaps interchangeable with <i>Docc</i>, attested in Doxey (Staffordshire) and Doxford (Northumberland). <i>Duke</i> could also represent Old English <i>Deowuc</i> (as in Deuxhill, Shropshire). A surname from <i>Marmaduke</i> is on record until at least 1881 and derives from the personal name <i>Marmaduke</i>, apparently an Anglo-Norman French pronunciation of Old Irish <i>Maolmaedóc</i> ‘devotee of <i>Maedóc</i>’; see   Duckett  .","Americanized form of Polish <b>Duk</b>: nickname from <i>dukać</i> ‘to stammer or falter’."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Duckett was born about 1451, in Cumberland, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Duckett. She married William Stanley about 1472, in Dalegarth, Cumberland, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"ABT 1451–":"umbes 1451–Surnud","1451–Female":"1451–Surnud","1450–1512":"1450–1512","1480–1556":"1480–1556","–Male":"Surnud","about 1480":"umbes 1480","1556":"1556","1512":"1512","ABT 1451":"umbes 1451","1451":"1451","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","about 1472":"umbes 1472","Dalegarth, Cumberland, England":"Dalegarth, Cumberland, England","Dalgarth, Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1451–":"noin 1451–Kuollut","1451–Female":"1451–Kuollut","1450–1512":"1450–1512","1480–1556":"1480–1556","–Male":"Kuollut","about 1480":"noin 1480","1556":"1556","1512":"1512","ABT 1451":"noin 1451","1451":"1451","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","about 1472":"noin 1472","Dalegarth, Cumberland, England":"Dalegarth, Cumberland, En